<!-- What is EBITDA -->
<div class="content-section">
  <h2>What is EBITDA? Definition & Meaning</h2>
  <p><strong>EBITDA</strong> stands for <strong>Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation, and Amortization</strong>. It is one of the most widely used financial metrics for evaluating a company's operating performance, stripping away the effects of financing decisions, tax jurisdictions, and non-cash accounting charges.</p>
  <p>Think of EBITDA as a company's "operating cash flow proxy." By removing interest (capital structure), taxes (jurisdiction-dependent), depreciation (asset age), and amortization (acquisition history), you get a cleaner picture of how well the core business actually generates earnings.</p>

  <h3>The EBITDA Formula</h3>
  <p>There are two standard ways to calculate EBITDA:</p>

  <div class="formula-box">
    <strong>Top-Down:</strong> EBITDA = Revenue − COGS − Operating Expenses + D&A
  </div>
  <div class="formula-box">
    <strong>Bottom-Up:</strong> EBITDA = Net Income + Interest + Taxes + D&A
  </div>

  <p>Both methods should produce the same result when using consistent financial statements. The top-down approach starts from the income statement's revenue line, while the bottom-up approach works backwards from net income.</p>

  <h3>EBITDA Margin</h3>
  <p>The <strong>EBITDA margin</strong> expresses EBITDA as a percentage of revenue: <code>EBITDA Margin = (EBITDA ÷ Revenue) × 100</code>. This ratio shows how much of each dollar of revenue converts into operating earnings before non-operating costs. A higher EBITDA margin indicates greater operational efficiency and pricing power.</p>

  <h3>What is Adjusted EBITDA?</h3>
  <p><strong>Adjusted EBITDA</strong> takes standard EBITDA and removes one-time, non-recurring, or unusual items to show "normalized" earnings. Common adjustments include restructuring charges, stock-based compensation, litigation costs, and one-time gains or losses. While adjusted EBITDA can provide a clearer picture of ongoing operations, investors should scrutinize what management chooses to adjust — aggressive adjustments can paint an artificially rosy picture.</p>

  <h3>EV/EBITDA — Enterprise Value to EBITDA</h3>
  <p>The <strong>EV/EBITDA ratio</strong> is the gold standard valuation multiple in mergers and acquisitions. It compares a company's enterprise value (market cap + debt − cash) to its EBITDA. Unlike the P/E ratio, EV/EBITDA accounts for debt levels, making it especially useful for comparing companies with different capital structures.</p>
  <p>General guidelines for EV/EBITDA interpretation:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Below 8x:</strong> Potentially undervalued — could indicate a value opportunity or fundamental problems</li>
    <li><strong>8–12x:</strong> Fair value range for most mature industries</li>
    <li><strong>12–20x:</strong> Premium valuation — market expects above-average growth</li>
    <li><strong>Above 20x:</strong> High-growth territory — common in tech and SaaS</li>
  </ul>
</div>

