<!-- Key Insights -->
<div class="content-section">
  <h2>5 Key Insights About EBITDA</h2>
  <div class="insights-grid">
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">1</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>EBITDA is not cash flow.</strong> Despite being called a "cash flow proxy," EBITDA ignores working capital changes, capital expenditures, and debt service. A company can have strong EBITDA and still run out of cash. Always pair EBITDA analysis with the cash flow statement.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">2</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>Adjusted EBITDA can be manipulated.</strong> Since there are no GAAP rules for adjusted EBITDA, management teams can exclude almost anything they want. Warren Buffett has been notably critical, calling EBITDA adjustments a way to "ichly dress up" earnings.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">3</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>Capital-intensive businesses need extra scrutiny.</strong> For companies with heavy fixed assets (airlines, manufacturing, telecom), D&A represents real economic costs of replacing equipment. EBITDA can significantly overstate the true earning power of these businesses.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">4</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>EV/EBITDA beats P/E for cross-company comparisons.</strong> Because it neutralizes capital structure and tax differences, EV/EBITDA is the preferred metric for comparing companies across borders or with different leverage levels — which is why it dominates M&A analysis.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-num">5</div>
      <div class="insight-text"><strong>EBITDA margin trends matter more than absolute values.</strong> A declining EBITDA margin over several quarters may signal rising costs, pricing pressure, or operational inefficiency — even if the absolute EBITDA figure is growing alongside revenue.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- FAQ -->
<div class="faq-section">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      What is EBITDA and what does it stand for?
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">EBITDA stands for Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation, and Amortization. It is a financial metric used to evaluate a company's operating performance by stripping out non-operating expenses like financing costs, tax environments, and non-cash charges. EBITDA provides a cleaner view of core business profitability and is the most widely used metric in M&A valuations.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      How do you calculate EBITDA?
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">There are two common EBITDA formulas. The top-down method starts from revenue: EBITDA = Revenue − COGS − Operating Expenses + Depreciation & Amortization. The bottom-up method starts from net income: EBITDA = Net Income + Interest + Taxes + Depreciation + Amortization. Both approaches should produce the same result when using consistent financial statement data.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      What is a good EBITDA margin?
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">A good EBITDA margin varies significantly by industry. Software and SaaS companies often achieve margins of 30–40%, while retail and restaurants typically operate at 5–15%. Generally, an EBITDA margin above 20% is considered strong across most industries, but the most meaningful comparison is always against direct competitors within the same sector.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      What is the difference between EBITDA and net income?
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">EBITDA excludes interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization to show operating performance before these costs. Net income is the true bottom line after all expenses are deducted. EBITDA is more useful for comparing companies with different capital structures and tax situations, while net income shows actual profitability available to shareholders after all obligations.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
      What does the EV/EBITDA ratio tell you?
      <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-a">The EV/EBITDA ratio (Enterprise Value to EBITDA) is a valuation multiple that compares a company's total value — including debt — to its operating earnings. A lower ratio (below 10x) may indicate undervaluation or a value opportunity, while a higher ratio (above 15x) suggests the market expects strong future growth. The S&P 500 average historically sits around 12–14x.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<script is:inline src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>

<script is:inline>
function formatNum(n) {
  if (n === null || n === undefined || isNaN(n)) return "—";
  if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e9) return "$" + (n / 1e9).toFixed(2) + "B";
  if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e6) return "$" + (n / 1e6).toFixed(2) + "M";
  if (Math.abs(n) >= 1e3) return "$" + (n / 1e3).toFixed(1) + "K";
  return "$" + n.toFixed(2);
}

function getVal(id) {
  var el = document.getElementById(id);
  if (!el) return 0;
  var v = parseFloat(el.value);
  return isNaN(v) ? 0 : v;
}

function showResult(containerId, rows) {
  var container = document.getElementById(containerId);
  var html = "";
  for (var i = 0; i < rows.length; i++) {
    var cls = "";
    if (rows[i].color === "pos") cls = " pos";
    if (rows[i].color === "neg") cls = " neg";
    html += '<div class="result-row"><span class="result-label">' + rows[i].label + '</span><span class="result-val' + cls + '">' + rows[i].value + '</span></div>';
  }
  container.innerHTML = html;
  container.style.display = "block";
}

function calcTopDown() {
  var revenue = getVal("td-revenue");
  var cogs = getVal("td-cogs");
  var opex = getVal("td-opex");
  var da = getVal("td-da");
  var mcap = getVal("td-mcap");
  var debt = getVal("td-debt");
  var cash = getVal("td-cash");

  var operatingIncome = revenue - cogs - opex;
  var ebitda = operatingIncome + da;
  var margin = revenue > 0 ? (ebitda / revenue) * 100 : 0;

  var rows = [
    { label: "Gross Profit", value: formatNum(revenue - cogs) },
    { label: "Operating Income (EBIT)", value: formatNum(operatingIncome) },
    { label: "EBITDA", value: formatNum(ebitda), color: ebitda >= 0 ? "pos" : "neg" },
    { label: "EBITDA Margin", value: margin.toFixed(1) + "%", color: margin >= 15 ? "pos" : "neg" }
  ];

  if (mcap > 0) {
    var ev = mcap + debt - cash;
    var evEbitda = ebitda > 0 ? ev / ebitda : 0;
    rows.push({ label: "Enterprise Value (EV)", value: formatNum(ev) });
    rows.push({ label: "EV/EBITDA", value: evEbitda.toFixed(1) + "x", color: evEbitda < 12 ? "pos" : evEbitda > 20 ? "neg" : "" });
  }

  showResult("td-result", rows);
}

function calcBottomUp() {
  var net = getVal("bu-net");
  var interest = getVal("bu-interest");
  var taxes = getVal("bu-taxes");
  var da = getVal("bu-da");
  var revenue = getVal("bu-revenue");

  var ebitda = net + interest + taxes + da;
  var ebit = net + interest + taxes;

  var rows = [
    { label: "EBIT (Operating Income)", value: formatNum(ebit) },
    { label: "EBITDA", value: formatNum(ebitda), color: ebitda >= 0 ? "pos" : "neg" }
  ];

  if (revenue > 0) {
    var margin = (ebitda / revenue) * 100;
    rows.push({ label: "EBITDA Margin", value: margin.toFixed(1) + "%", color: margin >= 15 ? "pos" : "neg" });
  }

  showResult("bu-result", rows);
}

function calcEVEbitda() {
  var mcap = getVal("ev-mcap");
  var debt = getVal("ev-debt");
  var cash = getVal("ev-cash");
  var ebitda = getVal("ev-ebitda");

  var ev = mcap + debt - cash;
  var ratio = ebitda > 0 ? ev / ebitda : 0;

  var rows = [
    { label: "Enterprise Value (EV)", value: formatNum(ev) },
    { label: "EV/EBITDA Ratio", value: ratio.toFixed(1) + "x" }
  ];

  showResult("ev-result", rows);

  var interpEl = document.getElementById("ev-interp");
  if (!interpEl) {
    interpEl = document.createElement("div");
    interpEl.id = "ev-interp";
    interpEl.className = "ev-interpretation";
    document.getElementById("ev-result").parentNode.appendChild(interpEl);
  }

  if (ebitda <= 0) {
    interpEl.style.background = "#30363d";
    interpEl.style.color = "#8b949e";
    interpEl.textContent = "Cannot calculate — EBITDA must be positive";
  } else if (ratio < 8) {
    interpEl.style.background = "rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.15)";
    interpEl.style.color = "#10b981";
    interpEl.textContent = "⬇ " + ratio.toFixed(1) + "x — Potentially Undervalued (below 8x)";
  } else if (ratio <= 12) {
    interpEl.style.background = "rgba(74, 143, 231, 0.15)";
    interpEl.style.color = "#4a8fe7";
    interpEl.textContent = "⚖ " + ratio.toFixed(1) + "x — Fair Value Range (8–12x)";
  } else if (ratio <= 20) {
    interpEl.style.background = "rgba(234, 179, 8, 0.15)";
    interpEl.style.color = "#eab308";
    interpEl.textContent = "📈 " + ratio.toFixed(1) + "x — Premium Valuation (12–20x)";
  } else {
    interpEl.style.background = "rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.15)";
    interpEl.style.color = "#ef4444";
    interpEl.textContent = "⬆ " + ratio.toFixed(1) + "x — Expensive / High-Growth (above 20x)";
  }
  interpEl.style.display = "block";
}

function toggleFaq(el) {
  var item = el.parentElement;
  var isOpen = item.className.indexOf("open") !== -1;
  if (isOpen) {
    item.className = "faq-item";
  } else {
    item.className = "faq-item open";
  }
}

/* Sector Chart */
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
  var ctx = document.getElementById("sectorChart");
  if (!ctx) return;

  var sectorLabels = [
    "Software & SaaS", "Telecom", "Oil & Gas", "Mining", "Pharma",
    "Utilities", "Healthcare", "Industrials", "Consumer Goods", "Retail", "Restaurants"
  ];
  var sectorMargins = [35, 34, 30, 29, 27, 25, 20, 16, 14, 9, 10];

  new Chart(ctx, {
    type: "bar",
    data: {
      labels: sectorLabels,
      datasets: [{
        label: "Avg EBITDA Margin (%)",
        data: sectorMargins,
        backgroundColor: "rgba(74, 143, 231, 0.7)",
        borderColor: "#4a8fe7",
        borderWidth: 1,
        borderRadius: 4
      }]
    },
    options: {
      responsive: true,
      maintainAspectRatio: true,
      indexAxis: "y",
      plugins: {
        legend: { display: false },
        tooltip: {
          callbacks: {
            label: function(context) {
              return context.parsed.x + "% EBITDA Margin";
            }
          }
        }
      },
      scales: {
        x: {
          beginAtZero: true,
          max: 45,
          ticks: { color: "#8b949e", callback: function(v) { return v + "%"; } },
          grid: { color: "rgba(48, 54, 61, 0.5)" }
        },
        y: {
          ticks: { color: "#c9d1d9", font: { size: 12 } },
          grid: { display: false }
        }
      }
    }
  });
});
</script>

